leg sections, and height capabilities to provide comfort and aid in medical procedures like ventilation or intubation. Manual adjustments in the ICU setting are generally sufficient for most basic operations, though they often come with multiple control points to facilitate necessary care. The demand for manual ICU beds is driven by their cost-effectiveness in comparison to electric models, while still meeting the essential requirements of the ICU environment. This segment is growing steadily, particularly in hospitals and healthcare facilities in emerging economies, where budget constraints and equipment availability drive preferences for manual options.</p><p>Despite being less sophisticated than electric models, manual ICU beds continue to play a vital role in supporting patients who do not require continuous high-tech interventions but still need specialized care. Manual beds in these settings provide healthcare providers with flexibility in adjusting the positioning of the patient, which is crucial in managing pressure ulcers, respiratory conditions, and mobility issues in critical cases. As healthcare facilities look to optimize resources while still maintaining high standards of care, the affordability and simplicity of manual ICU beds make them an attractive option. Furthermore, the growing prevalence of chronic diseases and the aging population contribute to the sustained demand for manual ICU beds, which help address the healthcare needs of both short-term and long-term intensive care patients.</p><h3>Non-intensive Care</h3><p>Non-intensive Care units, such as general medical wards, surgical recovery areas, and outpatient clinics, also heavily rely on manual hospital beds. These beds are typically used for patients who do not require constant monitoring or complex medical interventions but still need an adjustable bed to facilitate comfort during their stay. The manual bed in these settings allows caregivers to adjust the position of the patient for variou